<div id="review_3596423179" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3596423179" />
    <a title="Aditi Bhatt" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/47324726-aditi-bhatt"><img alt="Aditi Bhatt" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1600491738p2/47324726.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3596423179?book_show_action=true">Feb 11, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Aditi Bhatt" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Aditi Bhatt" href="/user/show/47324726-aditi-bhatt">Aditi Bhatt</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780670083497" href="/book/show/6971900-the-difficulty-of-being-good">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3596423179" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7691112256947445220">Honestly, I started this book a few years back and left after a few pages, restarted after some time, and left it, again. I just couldn&apos;t take in so much. But, third time&apos;s a charm! <br/>It is an extraordinary read based on the most extraordinary narrative of the Indian culture, the Mahabharata. We have read the epic, and even watched movies or dramas based on the same but Das reads between the lines and brings a detailed analysis of the characters and their characteristics that help elucidate the co</span>
  <span id="freeText7691112256947445220" style="display:none">Honestly, I started this book a few years back and left after a few pages, restarted after some time, and left it, again. I just couldn't take in so much. But, third time's a charm! <br />It is an extraordinary read based on the most extraordinary narrative of the Indian culture, the Mahabharata. We have read the epic, and even watched movies or dramas based on the same but Das reads between the lines and brings a detailed analysis of the characters and their characteristics that help elucidate the contemporary moral dilemmas.<br />I would like to share that earlier, I had this belief of Arjuna being the protagonist of the epic due to his overpowering portrayal in movies, books, and plays. But, after having read The Difficulty of Being Good, I found the character of Yudhishthir the most significant and inspiring for he is the one who believes in true Dharma however subtle it is. Das, in his conquest of understanding the meaning of Dharma brings up a value that is evident but difficult to pursue, that of being good. Consider, if Yudhishthir who had always followed Dharma and tried to be good in every manner had to suffer and struggle in exile and that too through a mischievous and unfair game of dice, what good is it to be good anyway for people so bad? Find out in the book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7691112256947445220" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


